{{efn
| name = Fear of tanks
| Nikolai Litvin, a Soviet anti-tank gunner present at the battle of Kursk, recalls his experience during the special training to overcome tank phobia. "The tanks continued to advance closer and closer. Some comrades became frightened, leaped out of the trenches, and began to run away. The commander saw who was running and quickly forced them back into the trenches, making it sternly clear that they had to stay put. The tanks reached the trench line and, with a terrible roar, clattered overhead&nbsp;... it was possible to conceal oneself in a trench from a tank, let it pass right over you, and remain alive." ({{harvnb|Litvin|Britton|2007|pp=12–13}}).
}}
